The cyclic voltammetry (CV) test of Pt–Pd/MWCNTs/BC was performed in PBS/glucose solution to prove the redox potential of GFC (Fig. S5c). When the glucose is absent, the CV curve has typical peaks for the hydrogen adsorption/desorption between − 0.6 and − 0.2 V versus SCE reference electrode. After adding the glucose in PBS, CV curve shows increased faradaic currents due to glucose oxidation in three regions. In anodic positive scan, glucose oxidation occurred in two regions, including the hydrogen desorption region from -0.6 to -0.4 V and the double-layer region from − 0.4 to 0.2 V. The third region for glucose oxidation occurred in the cathodic negative scan, i.e., hydrogen adsorption region from − 0.6 to 0.1 V [43]. These results indicated the qualified biochemical energy-harvesting ability of the as-fabricated GFC.
